Here's a complete example of an HTML form that demonstrates how to structure effective user instructions and handle different sensitive data types properly. This example includes a form for collecting a personal identification number (PIN) and a credit card number, along with other sensitive information.

**HTML Form Example:**
```html
<!-- Form Structure -->
<form id="sensitive-form">
  <!-- Form Header -->
  <h2>Secure Form Submission</h2>
  <p>Please fill out the form below to submit your sensitive information.</p>

  <!-- Personal Identification Number (PIN) Field -->
  <div class="form-group">
    <label for="pin">Personal Identification Number (PIN):</label>
    <input type="number" id="pin" name="pin" placeholder="Enter your PIN" required>
    <small class="form-text text-muted">Your PIN should be a 4-digit number.</small>
  </div>

  <!-- Credit Card Number Field -->
  <div class="form-group">
    <label for="credit-card">Credit Card Number:</label>
    <input type="number" id="credit-card" name="credit-card" placeholder="Enter your credit card number" required>
    <small class="form-text text-muted">Your credit card number should be a 16-digit number.</small>
  </div>

  <!-- Expiration Date Field -->
  <div class="form-group">
    <label for="expiration-date">Expiration Date:</label>
    <input type="month" id="expiration-date" name="expiration-date" required>
    <small class="form-text text-muted">Please enter your credit card's expiration date in the format MM/YYYY.</small>
  </div>

  <!-- Security Code Field -->
  <div class="form-group">
    <label for="security-code">Security Code:</label>
    <input type="number" id="security-code" name="security-code" placeholder="Enter your security code" required>
    <small class="form-text text-muted">Your security code should be a 3-digit number.</small>
  </div>

  <!-- Submit Button -->
  <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Submit</button>
</form>
```
**JavaScript Validation Example:**
```javascript
// Get the form element
const form = document.getElementById('sensitive-form');

// Add event listener to the form submission
form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  // Prevent default form submission
  e.preventDefault();

  // Get the form data
  const formData = new FormData(form);

  // Validate the form data
  const isValid = validateFormData(formData);

  // If the form data is valid, submit the form
  if (isValid) {
    // Submit the form data to the server
    submitFormData(formData);
  } else {
    // Display error message
    displayErrorMessage();
  }
});

// Function to validate form data
function validateFormData(formData) {
  // Check if the PIN is a 4-digit number
  if (!/^\d{4}$/.test(formData.get('pin'))) {
    return false;
  }

  // Check if the credit card number is a 16-digit number
  if (!/^\d{16}$/.test(formData.get('credit-card'))) {
    return false;
  }

  // Check if the expiration date is in the correct format
  const expirationDate = formData.get('expiration-date');
  if (!/^\d{2}\/\d{4}$/.test(expirationDate)) {
    return false;
  }

  // Check if the security code is a 3-digit number
  if (!/^\d{3}$/.test(formData.get('security-code'))) {
    return false;
  }

  // If all checks pass, return true
  return true;
}

// Function to submit form data to the server
function submitFormData(formData) {
  // Send the form data to the server using AJAX or a library like jQuery
  // For demonstration purposes, we'll just log the form data to the console
  console.log(formData);
}

// Function to display error message
function displayErrorMessage() {
  // Display an error message to the user
  const errorMessage = document.createElement('div');
  errorMessage.textContent = 'Error: Please correct the form errors.';
  document.body.appendChild(errorMessage);
}
```
**Security Measures:**

1. **Input Validation**: The JavaScript code validates the form data on the client-side to prevent malicious input from reaching the server.
2. **Data Encryption**: The form data is not encrypted in this example, but you should consider using a secure encryption algorithm (e.g., AES) to protect sensitive data.
3. **Secure Password Storage**: The form does not store passwords, but you should use a secure password hashing algorithm (e.g., bcrypt, Argon2) to store passwords securely.
4. **Tokenization**: The form does not tokenize sensitive data, but you should consider tokenizing sensitive data, such as credit card numbers, to reduce the risk of data breaches.

**User-Friendly Strategies:**

1. **Clear Labeling**: The form uses clear and concise labeling for each field to help users understand what information is required.
2. **Input Guidance**: The form provides input guidance, such as placeholder text and small text, to help users enter correct data.
3. **Error Handling**: The form displays an error message to the user when there are form errors.

This example demonstrates how to structure effective user instructions and handle different sensitive data types properly. However, you should consider implementing additional security measures, such as data encryption and tokenization, to protect sensitive data.

